  abstract = {Attosecond spectroscopy1\textendash 7can resolve electronic processes directly in time, but a movie-like space\textendash time recording is impeded by the too long wavelength (\textasciitilde 100 times larger than atomic distances) or the source\textendash sample entanglement in re-collision techniques8\textendash 11. Here we advance attosecond metrology to picometre wavelength and sub-atomic resolution by using free-space electrons instead of higher-harmonic photons1\textendash 7or re-colliding wavepackets8\textendash 11. A beam of 70-keV electrons at 4.5-pm de Broglie wavelength is modulated by the electric field of laser cycles into a sequence of electron pulses with sub-optical-cycle duration. Time-resolved diffraction from crystalline silicon reveals a\,{$<$}\,10-as delay of Bragg emission and demonstrates the possibility of analytic attosecond\textendash\aa ngstr\"om diffraction. Real-space electron microscopy visualizes with sub-light-cycle resolution how an optical wave propagates in space and time. This unification of attosecond science with electron microscopy and diffraction enables space\textendash time imaging of light-driven processes in the entire range of sample morphologies that electron microscopy can access.},
